quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The text-shadow Property[/h1]

The text-shadow property adds shadow to text. 
It takes four values: the first value defines the distance of the shadow in the [b]x (horizontal) direction[/b], the second value sets the distance in the [b]y (vertical) direction[/b], the third value defines the [b]blur[/b] of the shadow, and the fourth value sets the [b]color[/b]. 

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<h1>Text-shadow example</h1>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="527"]h1 {
   color: blue;
   font-size: 30pt;
[b]   text-shadow[/b]: 5px 2px 4px grey;
}[/code]
In the example above, we created a shadow using the following parameters:
[b]5px[/b] – the X-coordinate
[b]2px[/b] – the Y-coordinate 
[b]4px[/b] – the blur radius
[b]grey[/b] – the color of the shadow

[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2603" width="100%"]
[note]To add more than one shadow to the text, add a comma-separated list of shadows.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Create a text shadow with horizontal and vertical distance of 5px and blur radius of 2px:
[!raw!]

p {
{0}: 5px {1} {2};
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]text-shadow with Blur Effect[/h1]

When working with shadows, you can use any CSS-supported color format.

For the x and y offsets, various types of units can be used (like [b]px, cm, mm, in, pc, pt,[/b] etc). 
Negative values are also supported.

The example below creates a blue drop-shadow, two pixels higher than the main text, one pixel to the left of it, and with a 0.5em blur: 

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<h1>Text-shadow with blur effect</h1>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="528"]h1 {
   font-size: 20pt;   
   text-shadow: rgba(0,0,255,1) -1px -2px 0.5em; 
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2604" width="100%"]
[note]Internet Explorer 9 and earlier do not support the text-shadow property.[/note]
